\name{plot_grenades}
\alias{plot_grenades}
\title{Plot Grenades on a Map}
\usage{
plot_grenades(
  data,
  smoke = T,
  flash = T,
  incendiary = T,
  molotov = T,
  he = T,
  map
)
}
\arguments{
\item{data}{A data frame containing grenade data}

\item{smoke}{Logical indicating whether to plot smoke grenades (default is TRUE)}

\item{flash}{Logical indicating whether to plot flashbang grenades (default is TRUE)}

\item{incendiary}{Logical indicating whether to plot incendiary grenades (default is TRUE)}

\item{molotov}{Logical indicating whether to plot molotov grenades (default is TRUE)}

\item{he}{Logical indicating whether to plot HE grenades (default is TRUE)}

\item{map}{A character string specifying the name of the map to plot the grenades on}
}
\value{
A ggplot2 plot object
}
\description{
This function plots grenades on a map using ggplot2. It takes a data frame of grenade data, and optional parameters to specify which types of grenades to plot, and the map name.
}
